const e={title:"Journal",tagline:"A mood check-in and five short prompts — not a blank page.",what:"Journal combines a five-point daily mood check-in with five short, structured reflection prompts, plus a monthly mood calendar underneath. It isn't a free-form diary — the structure is the point, so a two-minute entry still captures the day honestly instead of turning into a blank page you avoid.",screenshot:"/help/journal/02-reflection-sections.png",howTo:[{heading:"Set today's mood",body:"Pick one of five — Rough, Low, Okay, Good, or Great — each with its own emoji. Only one mood per day, and only for today: past days are read-only, so you can't quietly rewrite how a day actually felt after the fact.",screenshot:"/help/journal/01-mood-picker.png"},{heading:"Fill in the five reflection sections",body:"Add lines one at a time and remove any with the X next to it:",list:['Wins — "What went well today?"','Grateful for — "1-3 things"','What mattered — "The point of today"',`Letting go of — "Offload what's draining"`,`Tomorrow's one thing — "A single priority"`],screenshot:"/help/journal/02-reflection-sections.png"},{heading:"Browse past entries from the monthly calendar",body:`Each logged day shows a mood-colored dot; click one to view that day's entry, clearly marked "Viewing {date} · past entries are read-only." Future days are disabled, and a Back to Today link returns you to the live, editable entry.`,screenshot:"/help/journal/03-mood-calendar.png"},{heading:"Watch your streak",body:`A flame-icon counter tracks consecutive days (including today, once logged) that have a mood entry. The footer under today's entry reads "Mood set · N points written today" once you've started, or "Tap a mood to log today and keep your streak" if you haven't yet.`},{heading:"Start-of-day setting",body:"Journal respects the same global Start-of-day setting as the rest of Anvil, so a late night before your configured day-boundary still logs to the right day."}],why:`A journal is only as useful as it is honest, and honesty about how a day felt is fragile — memory reshapes itself within hours. Journal is built around protecting that honesty, and around making reflection fast enough that it actually happens:

• Read-only past entries prevent revisionist self-narrative. It's very tempting, looking back, to upgrade a "Rough" day to "Okay" once the sting has faded, or to add a win you only thought of a week later. That temptation is understandable, but it quietly corrupts the one thing a mood log is for: an accurate record of how you actually felt, in the moment, without hindsight editing it. Locking past days protects the data from its own author.

• Five short prompts beat one open text box. A blank page invites either nothing (too much effort to start) or a wandering stream of consciousness (too much effort to review later). Five specific, small prompts lower the activation energy to write something today, while still covering wins, gratitude, meaning, release, and forward focus — the handful of angles reflection research keeps coming back to.

• Separating "Letting go of" from "Wins" keeps venting from crowding out gratitude. Without a dedicated place for what's draining you, it tends to leak into and dominate every other section. Giving it its own bullet list lets you offload it once and move on, instead of it coloring the whole entry.

• The mood calendar turns 30 individual days into one visible pattern. A single bad mood is just a bad day; a cluster of red dots across two weeks is a signal worth noticing. Neither is visible from inside any one day's entry — only the aggregated calendar view surfaces it.

• The streak rewards showing up, not writing well. Tapping a mood alone keeps the streak alive — there's no minimum word count or "quality bar." That's deliberate: consistency of reflection matters more than the polish of any single entry, and a bar set too high is a bar most people eventually stop clearing.

Used consistently, Journal is meant to give you an honest, dated trail of how you actually felt and what actually mattered — not the flattering retrospective memory tends to construct on its own.`};export{e as default};
